Wu You and his friends are among them. As of February 13, they had delivered medicines and protective equipment to more than 500 families seeking help.

The full text is 4,724 words and takes about 8 minutes to read

On January 25, Wu Yu hung up the "free medicine, food, mask" sign on the battery car. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Hsinking reporter, Xiao Weiwei, editor, Hu Jie

At 23pm on February 11th, the temperature on the second industrial road in Qingshan District, Wuhan, Wuhan was close to zero degrees Celsius. Under a dim streetlight, Wu, wearing a protective suit and mask, waited by the side of the road with a black plastic bag containing boxes of Oseltamivir, Moxifloxacin, Linghua Qingwen and a bottle of alcohol, this is a three-day dose for a home-quarantined patient with new coronary pneumonia.

A bunch of electric car lights appeared at the intersection. The woman on the bike took the plastic bag and said a few words of thanks. She stayed for less than 20 seconds before riding off into the night.

Under the epidemic, there is a need for home quarantine staff and quarantine points for patients, drug purchase has become difficult, emergency online help in the tens of thousands of posts. Many Wuhan citizens have spontaneously joined in the campaign to deliver free medicines to patients.

Wu You and his friends are among them.

Wu You, 26, is a middle school physics teacher in Wuhan who is still in an internship. Starting on January 25, Wu and Huang Xinyuan, a 19-year-old freshman, will ride a battery-powered bicycle and a bicycle through the streets of Wuhan, delivering medicines to people in hospitals, isolation points and neighborhoods.

As of February 13, they had delivered needed medicines and protective materials to more than 500 families seeking help.

"If you can send medicine for one day, you can send medicine for one day, " Wu said. "I hope the patients who get medicine from me can try again to hold on until they are diagnosed, admitted and recovered. "

━━━━━

"wanted to help out at first. "

Wu Youmeng to the need of people to send the idea of medicine, initially want to "help" to help.

On January 23, when Wuhan officially closed the Han Exit, Wu rushed to the pharmacy to buy masks and some commonly used medicines and sent them to her grandparents'home. GRANDPA's house saved some masks and said to him, "give them to people who need them. A person with ten thousand masks can only save one person, but a ten thousand can save ten thousand people. ".

He agreed with his grandfather. Since I had 500 disposable surgical masks in stock, I called all my friends in Wuhan and asked if they needed masks. A friend in the field asked him to help, to send some supplies and masks to the family, which in the eyes of Wu you is "with a foot" thing.

Back to the community to see the elderly did not wear masks, he sent two bags each.

At noon on January 25, Wu you and Huang Xinyuan stood at the intersection with more than 300 masks left to give to the elderly without masks. Huang remembers a woman in her 80s who put her hand over her nose and mouth and asked if there was a hotel near them. She said she had come out to look for an apartment because she had a fever and didn't want to infect her children. Huang Xinyuan gave her a bag of masks, pointed the direction, the corners of her eyes flashed tears, trembling to go.

"I came up with the idea of running errands for free to give people medicine and masks, " said Wu, who found a blank piece of paper with the words "medicine, food and masks for free" hanging in front of a battery truck. He posted a message on Weibo and his friends'circle, "In Hankou, I know a place with masks and medicine. I can go to Jiang'an District, Jianghan district, Qiaokou District. I can help you with the elderly. I can deliver my own people in other places without charge. ".

Wu's mobile phone started popping up with new messages, and by the time she finished a packed lunch at a convenience store, she had hundreds of comments and likes. One in five of the messages asked him to deliver medicine, and some offered to donate supplies.

He and Huang Xinyuan immediately division of Labor, he confirmed the information for help, according to the order of the message for help, one by one list of drugs they need. By Him pad money, Huang Xinyuan first ran to the pharmacy to buy medicine, two people then separately to send.

Huang Xinyuan to the nearby Business Pharmacy, Oseltamivir capsules have begun to limit purchases, a card can only buy a board, he ran three pharmacies, bought three board.

Wu Yu cut three board Oseltamivir capsules into a grain, packed in a disposable Paper Cup, first to five people for help, "first solve the urgent need, and so we bought the medicine, I will send them again. "

On the way to deliver the medicine, he received a message from the supplicant saying, "you can just leave the medicine at the door. I don't know why I have a fever. "

"I was also quite afraid, after all, to be infected with pneumonia patients to deliver medicine, but are on the road, first made to say, " Wu recalled at the time.

They delivered drugs from 2:00 p.m. to 10:00 p.m. , and only five. "I didn't plan the route, " Wu reflected. "I sent the car in the order of the messages. After I sent the family to the next house, it was the other way. It took eight hours to travel at least 25 kilometers, and four hours to recharge the battery car. "

By the next morning, he had received more than 1,600 comments and private messages, 10,000 likes, and more than 500 requests for help.

"At that moment, I felt like I was 'saving people' . "

From the beginning to send medicine, Wu you's Day is from reply 999 + new messages in the mobile phone to start.

Every message from the donor needs to be answered, and it matters whether they can provide free masks, alcohol, disinfectants and some medicines to those who ask for help. From January 27, donations will be sent out or delivered, and he will immediately post them on his micro blog, asking people in need to leave a message, which they will then provide free to patients, the elderly and children seeking help.

If it's an urgent request, the recipient's address is no more than 10 kilometers from his home, and he replies, "okay, coming. ". More requests for help were scattered in different districts of Wuhan, and he could only reply in unison, "sorry battery cars can't really deliver that far, give priority to patients, the elderly and infants. ".

Wu Yu to help, there are isolated, suspected or confirmed infection with new type of coronary pneumonia patients themselves, but also accompany the family members of the patients, more help the elderly home for help.

The medical and protective needs of those seeking help are not met on a daily basis. First of all, the medicine that can be bought in the drugstore every day is not stable, masks, alcohol and other materials ran out early, they have to go to the drugstore every day to try their luck. Huang Xinyuan near the home of more than a dozen pharmacies, he would make a trip every morning, there are two pharmacies unlimited Lianhua Qingwen capsules and Oseltamivir Granules, he had to buy dozens of each kind.

At 10 p.m. on Jan. 27, Wu received a call from Huang Shi asking for help. The Netizen said that his aunt and uncle had been diagnosed with new type of coronary pneumonia at their home in Wuhan, and that the two elderly people were already having difficulty breathing and speaking, there was no medicine left in the house, and the two old men could not go out to buy it even if they were isolated at home.

Wu Leisurely a listen to also anxious, he put on a raincoat to ride a bike to rush into the rain. When I found the exact location, it was nearly twelve o'clock. "Bang Bang" knocked on the door several times. When I heard the door open, I quickly left. When I got to the elevator, my aunt came over with the medicine and bowed deeply to him.

Out of the community, a cold wind blowing, Wu Yo a burst of fear, he took off his raincoat and threw into the roadside trash can, but also in case infected with the virus, Classical conditioning put the last point 84 disinfection water poured into the trash can.

After returning, he said to Huang Xinyuan, the future only to the patient delivery medicine.

Three days later, Wu received a message from the Huangshi Netizen, saying that it was a critical night, that the patients had been given medicine for several days when they were very helpless, and that they had now contacted the community, been hospitalized, and that things were getting better. "At that moment, I thought I was 'saving people, ' " Wu said

Hwang feels the same way. On January 30, a suspected patient quarantined in a hotel asked him to help buy Oseltamivir and other four drugs for pneumonia.

A few days in a row, Huang Xinyuan have to send medicine.

On Feb. 9, the supplicant told Huang on wechat that he had been transferred to a nearby shelter hospital for treatment. "They are isolated at home or in hotels until they are able to receive treatment, and the medicine we give them may be a lifeline, " Huang said.

Ride to your destination

Wu you deliver medicine to the door, will try to avoid direct contact with the person receiving the medicine. In the requests for help, the recipients were almost always suspected or confirmed cases of the new type of coronary pneumonia.

In Wu you began to deliver medicine a few days ago, the main delivery is the neighborhood of the home, are directly delivered to the door. His and Hwang's protective gear consisted only of an N95 mask, and he wore a helmet, which was pulled down by a glass cap, while the battery car was being charged by rubbing alcohol on his bare neck and hands.

He leaves his medicine at the door, takes a photo or video, knocks on the door a few times, gets a response and then leaves. He usually stays at the door for no more than 10 seconds. There are some strictly managed in and out of the community, he can only wait at the gate of the community or downstairs to wait for help, but will not directly meet them. "They themselves will pay special attention, for fear of infecting me, a long distance to let me put the drug on the ground. ".

Medicines, masks and alcohol prepared by Wu you before she set out. Photo courtesy of the respondents

To deliver medicine to hospitals and quarantined callers in hotels. He'll call security or a paramedic in the lobby. Occasionally, when patients at the isolation point were not given their room numbers or real names, he would place the drugs on a table in the hall, two meters away, waiting for them to come and get them.

On February 11, the longest day of his 18 days of compulsory medicine delivery, he ran more than 80 kilometers on his electric bicycle, charging it twice and returning home to nine people in need, a journey that took more than 15 hours.

At first, Wu's route to deliver medicine was limited to 35 kilometers, because his battery car can cycle 35 kilometers when fully charged, and even more so in low temperatures, reducing the range to 25 kilometers.

This time, Wu you decided to deliver medicine in Qingshan district, 30 kilometers away from her home. This was because of the seventh request for help sent by a person called April. She sent a list of confirmed cases from her family. She herself started to have a fever. There was no medicine at home, "I can't bear to say no, she's so helpless, " Wu said.

Before leaving at 11 a.m. on Feb. 11, Wu, who weighs more than 10 kilograms, packed a carton of medicine in his cart basket, and his online volunteers mapped out the route, from Kong Hon to Wuchang District to Qingshan District, Wuhan, the drugs were delivered to nine people in sequence, and the round trip was estimated to be 60 km.

But the actual distance traveled was a third more than estimated. At 7 p.m. , 17 kilometers from her home in April, Wu's battery car was down to one bar for the second time, and the distance between the three callers in Qingshan District, Wuhan was more than 10 kilometers.

Wu searched nearby and did not charge the pile, he in his own group of drug delivery help group for help, 2 km away by bike to a group of friends home, send batteries upstairs to charge. Knock on the door, the other side carrying a bowl of porridge to him, he took the bowl stand a little further, three after five after two eat, ran downstairs sitting on the stairs and so on, "special times we are quite afraid of contact with each other, but also help each other. ".

Huang Xinyuan's bicycle trip to deliver medicine has even greater restrictions on the distance he can travel. He can usually only deliver 10 kilometers away, and it will take him six or seven hours to get down from eight or nine places, "Legs have no feeling, do not feel tired, hungry at the convenience store to buy something to eat. ".

Huang Xinyuan, armed to the teeth, on his way to buy medicine

But for Wu and Huang, who can not drive, electric bikes and bicycles are the best vehicles they can find. All these difficulties were surmountable, and with only a short rest they carried the medicine of several families through the empty streets and alleys of Wuhan to their next destination.

Do what you have to do to keep going

In the comments, many netizens thanked him for his help with drug delivery, praised him, and reminded him to do a good job of protection.

Wu Youyou's behavior has also aroused some netizens'doubts. Someone on the Internet thought he was giving them away for free, and sent out an unusual request for help, asking for 100 face masks and dozens of boxes of Oseltamivir. After he posted on his microblog the prices of medicines and free supplies that needed to be charged, others questioned whether he was "putting on a show" , being a pharmacy man and making "national disaster money. ".

Wu started to pay attention to posting the price of each drug and the details of donated supplies. When he went to the drug store to buy immune proteins, vitamins or other drugs that might be needed, he sent photos and invoices to the people asking for help to confirm.

When Huang Xinyuan delivers medicine, some people who ask for help will give him a small red envelope above the price of the medicine. At first he did not dare to accept it. After discussing with Wu you, they will tell the person asking for help that the red envelope will be used as a donation, purchase medicines and supplies for other needy patients or the elderly.

On the way to deliver medicine, Wu sometimes recorded with Gopro, cut into a vlog video, uploaded to Weibo and friends circle, recorded when delivering medicine mood. "It's a normal, grim day, " he wrote in a friend group. "We all have to grit our teeth because there are patients not being treated. ".

Wu's father saw his circle of friends, just know he is free for patients to send medicine, he in his son's circle of friends message: "Do their best to persevere, but to protect themselves, do not exceed their tolerance. ".

Wu's friends and some netizens have also joined the ranks of volunteers offering free drugs. His team has seven online volunteers and four riders. Online volunteers in accordance with the administrative division, in the online collation of information for help, send him the needs and location of the help, he and the rider to discuss how to send. Now, their drug delivery area from the Jianghan District, Jiang'an District, Wuhan has covered all areas of the city.

He set up a group of more than 250 people who were too late to respond, and he planned to help them as best he could, and then others who needed help.

The atmosphere in the group changed greatly. At first, everyone was in a helpless mood, and kept sending out messages asking for help. The volunteers updated the information about the medicines available in Wuhan every day. Later, patients who were admitted to the shelter or other isolation areas began sharing their experiences, and psychological counselors joined in, leading the group to play Games and listen to music, "To help you relax, to distract you, to make you feel less helpless while you wait for your medicine, your therapy. ".

A single mother diagnosed with a new type of coronary pneumonia also joined in, she was isolated at home a few days short of medicine, Wu you sent her a few days of medicine and supplies. When she got better, she immediately told Wu that she wanted to donate the 20 N95 masks that her friend had sent her to others who needed them.

At 3:00 a.m. on Feb. 12, Wu finally arrived home and stood at the door of his home, packing his mask and protective clothing in garbage bags and spraying several rounds of alcohol. Since his community does not have a garbage can dedicated to recycling masks, he's GonNa have to do this initial decontamination.

He sat by the radiator for half an hour before he recovered and brought out three loaves of bread and a coke from the 24-hour convenience store downstairs. New Volunteer riders to join the Wechat, "just finished delivering medicine home, she got the medicine all cried. ".

"that still is worth, rest a brother. " Wu Leisurely replies to say.
